image.altText: A man poses with his fist

props.synopsis: A taekwondo instructor who allegedly murdered an entire family in Sydney will face a bedside court hearing today as New South Wales police continue investigating the motive.

title.children: Taekwondo instructor expected to face bedside court hearing after he was charged with murdering family

props.synopsis: Sixty years ago, people lost their minds as the Beatles landed in Sydney. Taylor Swift is the only artist to match the hysteria.

title.children: It feels like Swift is the biggest thing to ever land in Sydney — but how does the Eras tour compare to other iconic acts?

image.altText: A close-up of the Qantas logo on the tail of one of its planes. The sky behind it is clear.

props.synopsis: Qantas has recorded a 13 per cent fall in its post-tax profit to $873 million in the six months to December 2023, largely driven by lower airfares as its capacity returns to normal after the COVID-19 pandemic.

title.children: Qantas profit falls by 13 per cent to $873 million

image.altText: A large number of people, some police officers and some protesters, outside an old building

props.synopsis: A London court hears people living under authoritarian regimes "disappeared" after Julian Assange blended hacking with reporting, "stole vast amounts" of classified documents and published them on his WikiLeaks website.

title.children: People 'disappeared' after Assange and Wikileaks blended hacking with journalism, court hears

image.altText: Prime Minister Anthony Albanese

props.synopsis: Both Anthony Albanese and Peter Dutton will be sweating on the outcome of the March 2 by-election. It will determine their immediate political fortunes and the all-important momentum for 2024, writes David Speers.

title.children: What voters in Dunkley had to say about Albanese and Dutton before the high-stakes by-election

image.altText: A composite of a  tree-lined dirt track extending away into the bush, and a thin smiling woman with blonde hair.

props.synopsis: Police say they have added highly experienced detectives from multiple different policing divisions to the weeks-long search for missing mum Samantha Murphy.

title.children: Specialist Victorian detectives join Samantha Murphy investigation as community members mount new search

image.altText: A graphic of a laptop, two female students walking on campus, a woman on her phone, overlayed in red and white.

props.synopsis: A third of universities do not have task forces or committees set up to address sexual violence and many are not meeting the mark when it comes to transparency, according to a new report.

title.children: Transparent reporting of sexual violence on university campuses 'still really poor'

image.altText: A gloved hand holds a tiny, cowering bat.

props.synopsis: Insectivorous bats are tiny, quiet and worth about $63 million to the cotton industry. A study of the creatures, some of which are under threat, has been expanded in NSW.

title.children: To farmers, these tiny bats are worth a lot more than just their weight in pests

image.altText: A large pile of yellow tumbleweed covering a country road.

props.synopsis: Huge piles of tumbleweeds are surrounding houses, frustrating farmers and heightening fire risk in rural areas. But academics say very little can be done to wipe them out.

title.children: 'Hairy panic' tumbleweed blocking roads and choking farms in 'depressing' spread

image.altText: a big building with balconies

props.synopsis: Residents of the uninhabitable complex in Sydney will still incur major losses, but the deal will provide some resolution nearly five years after cracks were discovered in the building.

title.children: Mascot Towers ordeal close to end after five years as multi-million payout deal agreed for unit owners

image.altText: A 1950s black and white photo of a young man and young woman at a table with beers

props.synopsis: The pub has an important but flawed place in Australian culture, and it's also helped shape our politics.

title.children: From women chained to the bar to spitting in a beer: The history of pubs and politics

image.altText: A woman with blonde hair looks seriously at the camera. Behind her are two men and blue handprints.

props.synopsis: As the coronial inquest into the shooting death of Kumanjayi Walker resumes today, lawyers for former NT Police officer Zachary Rolfe have foreshadowed a series of objections he will raise when he takes the stand.

title.children: Days before his appearance at the Kumanjayi Walker inquest, Zachary Rolfe foreshadows claims to narrow his evidence

image.altText: Woman with cup in hand sits on couch with laptop on lap at home

props.synopsis: The extraordinary way working from home has transformed our labour market means it shouldn't be seen as a "favour" to workers, but as a favour to us all, writes Leonora Risse.

title.children: Working from home has transformed lives and the economy

image.altText: City office-workers and passers-by watch the ASX board in Sydney

props.synopsis: A fall on Wall Street is likely to send Australian stocks lower, while Qantas and Medibank are expected to reveal their earnings results. Follow the latest updates in our live blog.

title.children: ASX to drop, Wall Street slips ahead of Nvidia results

liveBlogKeyEvents.title: Qantas announces share buyback, half-yearly profit dips

image.altText: A salad with edamame beans, strands of carrot, lightly seared tuna and slices of avocado

props.synopsis: Low-carb diets are all the rage for weight loss. But do they really work?  And what are carbs anyway? Take our quiz to find out what the latest research suggests.

title.children: Are low-carb diets all they're cracked up to be? Maybe not

image.altText: A couple stand in a light filled lounge area with a dining table in the foreground and couch and window in the back

props.synopsis: While many might've considered Tylah and Dylan's rundown 1950s cottage a knockdown rebuild, they had other plans. The couple wanted to keep the home's character while turning it into an energy-efficient home.

title.children: Tylah and Dylan 'got laughed out of the room' when they shared their budget to turn their cottage into a passive house

image.altText: A composite image of three older-middle-aged white men in suits wearing glasses.

props.synopsis: It's been one of those weeks for Woolworths boss Brad Banducci, kicking off with the airing of a trainwreck Four Corners interview on Australian supermarket competition. But it all promises to end well, at least for him.

title.children: Echoes of Joyce and Lowe's early exits as Banducci heads for the $24 million door

image.altText: Sophie Harding celebrates a goal with teammates during an A-League Women game for the Western Sydney Wanderers.

props.synopsis: Sophie Harding was working as a disability support worker when she heard she was being called into the Matildas squad for the Olympic qualifiers. Now she's dreaming of a trip to Paris.

title.children: Sophie Harding's dream Matildas call-up 'a bittersweet moment' after father's death

image.altText: Woman drinks from water bottle.

props.synopsis: While the mercury reached almost 50C in parts of Australia this week, Tasmania is bracing for its own heatwave — albeit at a far less ferocious temperature — and it'll bring the worst fire conditions of the summer.

title.children: Tasmania braces for worst fire conditions it's faced all summer as temperatures set to hit mid-30s

image.altText: A man looks at the camera resting on the stairs.

props.synopsis: An Australian Federal Police officer will not be charged over the arrest of a protester who suffered serious injuries, after the conclusion of an internal investigation into the incident.

title.children: Police officer won't face criminal charges over arrest in which protester suffered serious injuries

image.altText: Michael Jefferies sits by himself on a bench with a tin wall behind him and a sketch of an Australian flag next to him.

props.synopsis: PTSD, anxiety and depression dogged Michael Jefferies after he left the military, but he was able to start healing in an unexpected place.

title.children: This soldier 'lost his identity' after leaving the army but found it again where he had been deployed

image.altText: A smiling woan in early middle age. She is wearing a head-covering and a singlet.

props.synopsis: Belinda Van Krevel, the sister of a man serving life sentences for two high-profile murders, has been jailed again after committing a crime with "disturbing similarities" to a previous offence.

title.children: Seaside city's dark past resurfaces as woman who had father murdered jailed for second stabbing

image.altText: A woman and three young boys sit under a tree.

props.synopsis: More than a week after deadly storms tore through Victoria, knocking out power to more than half a million customers, the lights are still out in some hard-hit areas of the state.

title.children: Victorians left in the dark after wild storms, but a permanent fix to power outages could cost billions

image.altText: Man in black shirt holds up phone for selfie

props.synopsis: Joshua Toole has been sentenced to six years' jail over his link to a commercial drug syndicate, after pleading guilty to supplying 1.9 kilograms of methamphetamine.

title.children: Meth-dealing brother of former NSW deputy premier jailed after judge hears about 'sometimes' violent upbringing

image.altText: A young white red-haired woman wearing a white beanie and vest poses in front of a backdrop of denim clothes

props.synopsis: "Smac" McCreanor's videos have had more than 1 billion views — and now you can see her work in a gallery for the first time at the NGV Triennial.

title.children: Meet Hydraulic Press Girl — the Aussie artist who gets 'squished' in viral videos

image.altText: Lyudmila Navalnaya standing outside in the snow with a sad look on her face.

props.synopsis: Lyudmila Navalnaya has been trying to retrieve her son's body since Saturday, following his death in a penal colony in Russia's far north a day earlier.

title.children: Alexei Navalny's mother files lawsuit with Russian court demanding release of son's body

image.altText: A young girl standing in front of destroyed buildings in the sand

props.synopsis: The 6.3-magnitude quake was one of the most destructive in the country's recent history, killing more than 2,000 people.

title.children: More than $600 million needed for western Afghanistan to recover from October earthquake, UN says

image.altText: ATO Commissioner Chris Jordan speaks at the National Press Club.

props.synopsis: Outgoing ATO boss Chris Jordan said "Australians love their work-related expense deductions" and abolishing them in favour of lower personal income tax rates "would be a big step".

title.children: Outgoing ATO boss says getting rid of work-related expense deductions could simplify the tax system — but it's 'a big step'

image.altText: Two men celebrate after winning a cricket match

props.synopsis: New Zealand sets Australia an imposing total in Wellington but a mighty innings from Mitch Marsh and some final over heroics from Tim David secured the tourists an epic victory.

title.children: Tim David the hero as Australia triumphs over New Zealand in last-ball thriller

image.altText: A portrait of Ewen MacIntosh in The Office.

props.synopsis: Actor Ewen MacIntosh, who was best known for playing Keith Bishop in the British comedy The Office, has died aged 50.

title.children: Ricky Gervais pays tribute to 'very funny' The Office star Ewen MacIntosh

image.altText: A creature with dozens of purple and white tentacles sitting on sand.

props.synopsis: Experts say the WA-first sighting of a rare crab and photos of a strange anemone on Broome's beaches highlight the untapped wonders off Australia's coasts.
